📖 Theory
What is SSH?

SSH (Secure Shell) is a secure protocol used to connect to remote Linux servers.

Example:

Laptop
    │
    │ SSH
    ▼
Ubuntu Server

Default SSH Port:

22
🛠️ Task 1 – Check SSH Status

Ubuntu

sudo systemctl status ssh

Start SSH

sudo systemctl start ssh

Enable at boot

sudo systemctl enable ssh
🛠️ Task 2 – Find Your IP
hostname -I

or

ip addr
Task 3 – Connect to Remote Server
ssh username@server-ip

Example

ssh ubuntu@192.168.1.100

Exit

exit
🛠️ Task 4 – Generate SSH Key
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"

If Ed25519 isn't supported:

ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096

Keys are stored in:

~/.ssh/

Check:

ls ~/.ssh
🛠️ Task 5 – Copy SSH Key

Automatic:

ssh-copy-id username@server-ip

Manual:

cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub

Append the key to:

~/.ssh/authorized_keys

on the remote server.

🛠️ Task 6 – Login Without Password
ssh username@server-ip

If configured correctly, no password is required.

🛠️ Task 7 – SSH Config

Create:

nano ~/.ssh/config

Example

Host dev-server
    HostName 192.168.1.100
    User ubuntu
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519

Now connect using:

ssh dev-server
🛠️ Task 8 – Copy Files

Upload:

scp backup.tar.gz ubuntu@server-ip:/home/ubuntu/

Download:

scp ubuntu@server-ip:/var/log/syslog .
🛠️ Task 9 – Execute Remote Commands
ssh ubuntu@server-ip "uptime"

Another example:

ssh ubuntu@server-ip "df -h"
🛠️ Task 10 – SSH Agent

Start:

eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"

Add key:

ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519

List keys:

ssh-add -l
🔒 SSH Security Best Practices

Edit:

sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config

Recommended settings:

PermitRootLogin no

PasswordAuthentication no

PubkeyAuthentication yes

MaxAuthTries 3

PermitEmptyPasswords no

Restart:

sudo systemctl restart ssh
